Empirical inference for agent-based models, where are we going next?

Empirical induction in complex systems

What is a model?

  • A model is:
    • a collection of causal relationships
    • embedded in algorithms
    • modulated by parameters
    • counterfactual
  • Data is:
    • factual
  • Estimation/Calibration
    • Set counterfactual parameters through factual observations

The problem of induction

  • Set counterfactual parameters through factual observations
    • Learn about what could have happened given what happened
  • Let’s do it! Can it be done?
    • Depends on the assumed model
    • Depends on the availability of data
    • Depends on the technique used
      • Sometimes it cannot be done
      • Most of the time, it can only be done in parts
    • under-identification

Macroeconomics example

Canova, Fabio, and Luca Sala. “Back to square one: Identification issues in DSGE models.” Journal of Monetary Economics 56.4 (2009): 431-449.

  • Weak identification pervasive in DSGE
  • Validation techniques (comparing impulse responses out-of-sample) do not help
  • \(\to\) wrong with high degree of confidence

What to do?

  • Accept identification issues
    1. Use methods that are honest about unknown parameters
    2. Try to see if anything can be said with some/all unknown parameters
  • Add assumptions to make it more identifiable
    • Manski’s law of decreasing credibility
    • “Stronger assumptions yield conclusions that are more powerful but less credible”

Estimation methods

Kinds of parameters

  • Some can be set directly
  • Others need some estimation
  • Often we don’t know

Example fishing boats

  • Building an ABM of boats going fishing
  • Key parameter: number of boats
  • If we have data on number of boats: no estimation needed
    • what if boats are heterogeneous?
    • size, captain’s skill, quality of maintenance…
  • Ignore heterogeneity \(\to\) lack of realism?
  • Accept heterogeneity \(\to\)
    1. more complexity
    2. more parameters
  • Abstract away \(\to\)
    1. ignore boats, focus on “fishing power”

Public health example

Murray, E. J., Robins, J. M., Seage, G. R., Freedberg, K. A., & Hernán, M. A. (2020). The Challenges of Parameterizing Direct Effects in Individual-Level Simulation Models.

Targets

The main practical challenge

  • In equation-based models \[ f(\theta) \]
    • Make some assumptions about data \(x\) such that we can write likelihood function \[ L(\theta | x) \]
    • Find the parameters \(\theta\) that maximize the likelihood

In simulation methods

  • Likelihood is unknown and intractable
  • Need to focus on likelihood-free methods

Simulation alternatives

  • By target
    • Curve Matching
    • Likelihood substitutes
    • Summary statistics
  • By method
    • Accept/Reject
    • Minimization
    • Meta-modelling
    • Regression-based

What we want in a method

  • Efficiency
  • Theoretical guarantees
  • Confidence intervals
  • Can test its identification performance

Naive method

  • Match a simulated “curve” against a real one
    • “minimize mean square error”

  • Baptista, Rafa, et al. “Macroprudential policy in an agent-based model of the UK housing market.” (2016).

Naive method

  • Weaknesses:
    • No confidence intervals
    • Local minima and under-identification
    • Expensive to test
  • Consequences
    • Sensitivity analysis needs to be wide
    • Validation needs to be thorough

Likelihood alternatives

  • ABMs likelihoods are unknown
  • If your model is very fast:
    • MC likelihood
    • Pseudo-likelihood

Example: animal tracking

Hooten, M., Wikle, C., & Schwob, M. (2020). Statistical Implementations of Agent‐Based Demographic Models. International Statistical Review, https://doi.org/10.1111/insr.12399

  • Tracking a set of animals
    • Each step, they survive with probability \(\theta\)
    • Each step, if alive, their tracker reports their presence with probability \(p\)
  • Given a set of track time series
    • What are \(\theta\) and \(p\)

Example: animal tracking (2)

Example: animal tracking (3)

  • MC Likelihood:
    • Pick \(\theta,p\)
    • Run many simulations
    • Likelihood is how many individual time series match entirely
  • Pseudo-likelihood:
    • Pick \(\theta,p\)
    • Run many simulations
    • Likelihood is how many observations at each time point for each individual match

Likelihood alternatives - problems

  • Computational expensive
  • Only point estimates:
    • Need to validate
    • Need to do sensitivity analysis
  • In large time series exact matches are very unlikely

Summary statistics

  • Summarise real world data into a set of statistics
  • Summarise synthetic data into the same set
  • Get them as close as possible: \[ \min (\beta_{\text{real}} - \beta_{\text{abm}}(\theta))^T W (\beta_{\text{real}} - \beta_{\text{abm}}(\theta)) \]
  • Two conceptual schools of thought:
    • Indirect inference
    • Approximate Bayesian Computation
  • Connection to “Pattern Oriented Modelling”

Indirect Inference (example)

  • Zhao, Linqiao. A model of limit-order book dynamics and a consistent estimation procedure. Diss. Carnegie Mellon University, 2010.

Methods

Accept/Reject

  • Set a distance \(\epsilon\) to the target
    1. Randomly sample parameters \(\theta\)
    2. Run the model with the random parameters
    3. Accept if you are less than \(\epsilon\) away from your target
  • Very inefficient!
  • Generates confidence intervals
  • Can be made “Bayesian” (ABC) by adding priors
  • Easy to test

Simple Rejection ABC, example:

van der Vaart, E., Beaumont, M. A., Johnston, A. S. A., & Sibly, R. M. (2015). Calibration and evaluation of individual-based models using Approximate Bayesian Computation. Ecological Modelling, 312, 182–190. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ecolmodel.2015.05.020

Complicated rejection example:

Seri, R., Martinoli, M., Secchi, D., & Centorrino, S. (2021). Model calibration and validation via confidence sets. Econometrics and Statistics, 20, 62-86.

Minimization

  • Tune the parameters \(\theta\) so that:
    • Maximize likelihood
    • Minimize Error
    • Minimize summary statistics distance
  • Many options:
    • Genetic Algorithms
    • Hill-climbers
    • Particle swarms

Minimization - example

Robles, J. F., Bermejo, E., Chica, M., & Cordón, Ó. (2021). Multimodal Evolutionary Algorithms for Easing the Complexity of Agent-Based Model Calibration. Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation, 24(3).

Meta-modelling

  • Tune the parameters \(\theta\) so that:
    • Maximize likelihood
    • Minimize Error
    • Minimize summary statistics distance
  • Do not do it directly
    • Instead train an intermediate Gaussian Process
    • Maximize that surface instead

Meta-modelling - example

Parry, Hazel R., Christopher J. Topping, Marc C. Kennedy, Nigel D. Boatman, and Alistair W.A. Murray. ‘A Bayesian Sensitivity Analysis Applied to an Agent-Based Model of Bird Population Response to Landscape Change’. Environmental Modelling and Software 45 (July 2013): 104–15. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.envsoft.2012.08.006.

Regression method

  • Avoid minimizing/weighing altogether
  • Run model many times (like rejection ABC)
  • Create a table of parameters \(\to\) summary statistics
  • Use a regression to do the inverse connection, summary statistics \(\to\) parameters
    • Gets you confidence intervals on all parameters
    • Easy to test identification
    • Not efficient
  • Carrella, E., Bailey, R., & Madsen, J. (2020). Calibrating Agent-Based Models with Linear Regressions. Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation, 23(1). https://doi.org/10.18564/jasss.4150

New regression methods

  • Neural networks very popular now
    • BayesFlow: bayesflow
    • SNPE-C: sdi

Neural Network - examples

Shiono, T. (2021). Estimation of agent-based models using Bayesian deep learning approach of BayesFlow. Journal of Economic Dynamics and Control, 125, 104082.

Analysis paralysis

  • Too many methods! What shall I choose?
  • Carrella, E. (2021). No Free Lunch when Estimating Simulation Parameters. Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation, 24(2).
  • No free lunch
    • Best “method” differs between models
    • Every method is the “best” in at least one case
    • Half the ABM tested were only partially identified

Conclusion

Priorities

  1. Figure out what parameters been identified
    • confidence intervals
    • cross-validation
  2. Carry over that uncertainty when doing policy analysis
    • Sensitivity analysis bounds
  3. Validate
